00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:02.440
We'll start with, what is MLOps?

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:10.440
MLOps is the combination of machine learning and development operations, which I find is

00:07:10.440 --> 00:07:16.440
not the most useful frame of mind when thinking about, like, what does this word really mean?

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:23.440
So I think a better definition is that MLOps is a set of practices to deploy and maintain

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:28.440
machine learning models in production reliably and efficiently.

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:31.440
And these practices are hard.

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:37.440
When I started deploying models with Kubernetes, I struggled with a lot of the tools that were

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:38.440
out there.

00:07:38.440 --> 00:07:42.440
I felt that as a data scientist, these tools weren't really made for me.

00:07:42.440 --> 00:07:45.440
They were made for a different persona.

00:07:45.440 --> 00:07:52.440
So I actually ended up leaving that job, and I started working on tools for data scientists

00:07:52.440 --> 00:08:01.440
to help them kind of build the skills to develop and deploy models.

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:06.440
So currently I work on a package called Vetiver, and it's helping data scientists deploy models

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:08.440
in both Python and R.

00:08:08.440 --> 00:08:13.440
So this means you can install the package Vetiver in RStudio.

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:20.440
You can also install the package Vetiver from PyPI.

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:23.440
So let's look at this data science workflow right now.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:25.440
So you start by collecting data.

00:08:25.440 --> 00:08:31.440
You're getting your data from the cloud or the ground or wherever people are getting

00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:33.440
data these days.

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:39.440
And then there are great tools out there to help you understand and clean your data, things

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:49.440
like the tidyverse or data table in R or Pandas or NumPy or Suba in Python.

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:53.440
Once your model or once your data has been cleaned and you have a good understanding

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:57.440
of what's in there, you can train and evaluate your model.

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:04.440
Once again, there are great tools out there like TidyModels and Carrot in R and Scikit-learn

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:07.440
and PyTorch in Python.

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:10.440
And let's look at the code.

