if it's a patriotic ad or they're a celebrity or danger or animals.

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:43.440
So we load in this data, and it looks like this.

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:49.440
We have our like count, and everything else is true or false.

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:53.440
Once we have our data loaded, we're going to, you know, train and tune our model.

00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:57.440
So we're splitting it up into a test and training set.

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:01.440
So this is to make sure that we're not giving our model the answers when we're trying to

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:04.440
teach it what it's doing.

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:07.440
We have a little bit of preprocessing.

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:11.440
So you saw that those columns were true and false.

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:13.440
Models don't speak English.

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:16.440
So we need to translate that into some numbers.

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:19.440
And that ordinal encoder is doing that for us.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:22.440
From there, we're going to use a random forest regressor.

00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:25.440
So we're going to put those numbers in, train the model.

00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:28.440
We're ready to go.

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:30.440
We're actually going to put these together in a pipeline.

00:10:30.440 --> 00:10:34.440
And this is important because you want to deploy your feature engineering if you are

00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:38.440
fitting it and the model together.

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:44.440
If we're learning from data, this is all going to be deployed at once.

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:46.440
So we saw the beginning of this cycle.

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:51.440
You know, we have really clear tools of what to use for data scientists.

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:58.440
But it gets a little bit hazy of where should we go next after we have built our model.

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:05.440
And these MLOps practices that we're looking at, Benever focuses on three of them.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:11.440
It focuses on versioning, deploying, and monitoring a model.

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:14.440
So MLOps is versioning.

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:16.440
So we are amazing data scientists.

00:11:16.440 --> 00:11:18.440
We have built our model.

00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:23.440
And we have named it model like things happen sometimes.

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:27.440
And once we have trained our model, we're ready to deploy it.

00:11:27.440 --> 00:11:29.440
So we have our model final.

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:33.440
And then we realize maybe we need to do some edits.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:35.440
We need to tune some more parameters.

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:38.440
So we have our model final version 2.

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:42.440
And then actually there's been some data drift or something.

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:46.440
And there's still more to be done with this model.

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:51.440
And now we have model final version 2 actually this time.

00:11:51.440 --> 00:11:53.440
We're ready to deploy.

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:54.440
Okay.

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:56.440
So this lacks context.

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:58.440
And it's not scalable for one model.

00:11:58.440 --> 00:12:03.440
So what happens when you have hundreds of models?

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:05.440
This is not going to work.

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:10.440
So when you're versioning a model, you're going to package up a few different things together.

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:12.440
So you're going to include the model object.

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:14.440
So the model itself.

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:20.440
You're going to have a hash for a really more robust version than this.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:25.440
And then you're going to have some metadata to give this model context.

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:29.440
Managing change in models is what versioning is all about.

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:33.440
It's important to think about versioning across time.

00:12:33.440 --> 00:12:41.440
Because if you have a model version 1, version 2, version 3, you can imagine how the entire team of data scientists looks.

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:44.440
It's also important if you have different implementations.

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:48.440
Say a staging and a production server.

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:55.440
Really, any time you have multiple models, some sort of versioning is going to help you organize this.

00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:57.440
It's going to make it easier for yourself.

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:04.440
And it's going to make it easier for you to communicate and share these models with the rest of your team.

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:09.440
So in Vetiver, we have a secret weapon called pins.

00:13:09.440 --> 00:13:11.440
This is another package developed by my team.

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:14.440
And it's all about versioning.

00:13:14.440 --> 00:13:17.440
So for pins, you kind of have to think about it as a board.

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:21.440
And you're going to take these models and you're going to pin them on the board.

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:23.440
So we have our model board set up.

00:13:23.440 --> 00:13:25.440
It's a temporary board.

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:29.440
We have to allow explicitly for pickle models to be read.

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:31.440
It's because of arbitrary code.

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:36.440
If that last sentence was like, why are you talking about pickles right now, don't worry about it.

00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:38.440
So our model board is ready.

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:41.440
And now we're going to make a Vetiver model.

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:49.440
And this is because when you're training a model, you actually have a lot of context that you can put together into one object.

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:52.440
So we're putting our pipeline in here.

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:54.440
We're going to give it a name called ads.

00:13:54.440 --> 00:13:59.440
And we're going to give it a input data prototype called X-train.

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:01.440
Or it's just like the X-train data.

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:12.440
And this input data prototype is important because like we saw from Toast, sometimes the real world data looks different than what we trained with.

00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:24.440
And we want this deployable model object of Vetiver to be aware of what the original data is supposed to look like so you can get better errors when things go wrong.

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:26.440
When things go wrong.

00:14:26.440 --> 00:14:33.440
So once this Vetiver model has been created, you're going to pin write.

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:34.440
You have your model board.

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:36.440
You're going to write this pin onto it.

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:40.440
And I promised that this works in R as well.

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:46.440
And I think it's important to show you guys kind of how similar this code looks.

00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:49.440
So in R, you have your libraries of Vetiver and pins.

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:57.440
You have your temporary board, your Vetiver model, and your Vetiver pin writing this model to the board.

00:14:57.440 --> 00:15:04.440
We worked really hard to make sure that each of these packages feels good in the native language.

00:15:04.440 --> 00:15:07.440
But that it's also easy for teams that are multilingual.

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:17.440
If data scientists need to hop between languages, you don't have to learn an entirely new framework.

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:19.440
So I promised you some metadata.

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:21.440
Here's some metadata.

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:25.440
From just these few lines of code, we have gathered a lot of information here.

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:27.440
You can see there's a title.

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:28.440
The model's name is ads.

