00:16:41.440 --> 00:16:46.440
However, when these models are up in Azure or S3 or wherever,

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:50.440
you still have to pull them down, load the model, get your data,

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:52.440
like put it in the model, make the prediction.

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:55.440
And it feels clunky.

00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:58.440
So we need a better way than just saving models,

00:16:58.440 --> 00:17:01.440
although this is an important place to start.

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:04.439
So we want to deploy the models as well.

00:17:04.439 --> 00:17:07.439
And deploying just means putting a model in production,

00:17:07.439 --> 00:17:11.439
which is kind of a loaded sentence because what is production?

00:17:11.439 --> 00:17:15.439
It looks very different for different people.

00:17:15.439 --> 00:17:19.439
But in general, we're going to say that deploying a model is anywhere

00:17:19.439 --> 00:17:21.439
that is not on your local laptop.

00:17:21.439 --> 00:17:24.439
This could be inside of an application.

00:17:24.439 --> 00:17:31.439
This can be just kind of living somewhere or anywhere in between.

00:17:31.439 --> 00:17:35.439
So the idea of data science workflows are directly opposite

00:17:35.439 --> 00:17:38.439
of software engineering best practices.

00:17:38.439 --> 00:17:43.439
Software engineers are very interested in reusable, testable,

00:17:43.439 --> 00:17:50.439
like very strongly put together, like super robust deployments.

00:17:50.439 --> 00:17:54.439
Like they want to be certain that this is going to act the way

00:17:54.439 --> 00:17:56.439
that they expect it to.

00:17:56.439 --> 00:17:59.439
And data scientists are a little more experimental.

00:17:59.439 --> 00:18:00.439
We want to move fast.

00:18:00.439 --> 00:18:02.439
We want to make lots of different models.

00:18:02.439 --> 00:18:05.439
We want to be agile when data changes.

00:18:05.439 --> 00:18:09.439
So there's a little bit of tension there.

00:18:09.439 --> 00:18:11.439
When we're thinking of making an application,

00:18:11.439 --> 00:18:15.439
if you told your software engineers that actually whenever I update my model,

00:18:15.439 --> 00:18:18.439
we're going to copy and paste the code from my Jupyter Notebook

00:18:18.439 --> 00:18:21.439
into the application, and it's going to go great,

00:18:21.439 --> 00:18:24.439
they might kind of look at you funky.

00:18:24.439 --> 00:18:27.439
We don't want to be copying and pasting code between applications,

00:18:27.439 --> 00:18:31.439
and we don't want to be emailing model files to each other.

00:18:31.439 --> 00:18:34.439
So we're going to use something called a REST API.

00:18:34.439 --> 00:18:37.439
A REST API is just a simple way to have machines

00:18:37.439 --> 00:18:39.439
communicate with each other.

00:18:39.439 --> 00:18:42.439
It's standardized, and they're useful because these endpoints

00:18:42.439 --> 00:18:46.439
can be hosted in computational environments

00:18:46.439 --> 00:18:49.439
that are completely independent of an application.

00:18:49.439 --> 00:18:53.439
So this makes software engineers happy because your endpoint

00:18:53.439 --> 00:18:56.439
will stay the same even as you update your model,

00:18:56.439 --> 00:18:59.439
and so the application code won't change,

00:18:59.439 --> 00:19:03.439
and you can kind of live in your world of your own API

00:19:03.439 --> 00:19:05.439
if you are a data scientist.

00:19:05.439 --> 00:19:08.439
And these APIs are also testable,

00:19:08.439 --> 00:19:13.439
and they are pretty easy to put together.

00:19:13.439 --> 00:19:17.439
So we have our Vetiver model from before, still called V.

00:19:17.439 --> 00:19:21.439
And to set this model up locally in our API,

00:19:21.439 --> 00:19:25.439
we'll have vetiver-api-v.run.

00:19:25.439 --> 00:19:29.439
This is built off of FastAPI, which is a very popular framework,

00:19:29.439 --> 00:19:33.439
similar to Flask, but a little bit more lightweight.

00:19:33.439 --> 00:19:37.439
So when you're running your application or your API endpoint,

00:19:37.439 --> 00:19:41.439
you'll get a browser window that looks kind of like this.

00:19:41.439 --> 00:19:45.439
You can see at the top it's 127.0.0.1.

00:19:45.439 --> 00:19:47.439
It's on my local machine.

00:19:47.439 --> 00:19:51.439
This is all a self-documenting API.

00:19:51.439 --> 00:19:53.439
So it has the name of the model here.

00:19:53.439 --> 00:19:55.439
It has the pipeline class.

00:19:55.439 --> 00:19:58.439
We can see where the server is hosted.

00:19:58.439 --> 00:20:03.439
But if you scroll down, you'll see this predict endpoint.

00:20:03.439 --> 00:20:05.439
And this predict endpoint is kind of fun.

00:20:05.439 --> 00:20:10.439
You can interact with it to make sure the model in your API endpoint

00:20:10.439 --> 00:20:12.439
is behaving as expected.

00:20:12.439 --> 00:20:17.439
We can see what happens if the model is funny and has animals.

00:20:17.439 --> 00:20:19.439
We can also look at the response headers

00:20:19.439 --> 00:20:22.439
and curl to interact with this model,

00:20:22.439 --> 00:20:24.439
which is useful if you need to pass these off

00:20:24.439 --> 00:20:27.439
to somebody else on your team.

00:20:27.439 --> 00:20:28.439
But this is still local.

00:20:28.439 --> 00:20:31.439
127.0.0.1, that's my local machine.

00:20:31.439 --> 00:20:35.439
So we want to deploy it somewhere else.

00:20:35.439 --> 00:20:38.439
There is a one-liner for RStudio's pro product.

00:20:38.439 --> 00:20:40.439
It is deploy-rs-connect.

00:20:40.439 --> 00:20:42.439
You give it the connect server.

00:20:42.439 --> 00:20:44.439
You give it the board, the pin name,

00:20:44.439 --> 00:20:47.439
and the version you are deploying.

00:20:47.439 --> 00:20:50.439
And these deployments are strongly versioned.

00:20:50.439 --> 00:20:55.439
So why versioning is so important is if we want to update a model

00:20:55.439 --> 00:20:58.439
or roll back, we just have to change that version there.

00:20:58.439 --> 00:21:03.439
So in this one-liner, our model can be on connect.

00:21:03.439 --> 00:21:06.439
So this is what it looks like before on my local machine.

00:21:06.439 --> 00:21:11.439
You can see at the top, 127.0.0.1 is the URL.

00:21:11.439 --> 00:21:14.439
And here's what it looks like on connect.

00:21:14.439 --> 00:21:17.439
And it's kind of funny because I can click back and forth

00:21:17.439 --> 00:21:19.439
and pretty much it looks the exact same.

00:21:19.439 --> 00:21:21.439
But this is an important piece.

00:21:21.439 --> 00:21:25.439
Things break very quickly when your development environment

00:21:25.439 --> 00:21:30.439
looks nothing like what your production environment looks like.

00:21:30.439 --> 00:21:34.439
So this is really a nod to the reproducibility and stability of APIs.

00:21:34.439 --> 00:21:40.439
If I test it locally and deploy it, it should look and feel the same,

00:21:40.439 --> 00:21:42.439
even if it's hosted in a different location.

00:21:42.439 --> 00:21:45.439
But I understand that not everyone is a connect user.

00:21:45.439 --> 00:21:49.439
So I had to build different ways for people to deploy this

00:21:49.439 --> 00:21:51.439
to other locations.

00:21:51.439 --> 00:21:54.439
So if you do vetiver write app, give it the board and the pin name,

00:21:54.439 --> 00:21:57.439
you can also add the version.

00:21:57.439 --> 00:22:00.439
It will write an app.py file that has all the information

00:22:00.439 --> 00:22:02.439
to create this API.

00:22:02.439 --> 00:22:06.439
And a lot of cloud providers will take this app.py file

00:22:06.439 --> 00:22:08.439
and they'll run it for you so you can bring this

00:22:08.439 --> 00:22:10.439
to different cloud environments.

00:22:10.439 --> 00:22:13.439
And for some clouds, this is enough.

00:22:13.439 --> 00:22:17.439
But others want a Docker file.

00:22:17.439 --> 00:22:21.439
So if you've written your app.py file, you can also write a Docker file

00:22:21.439 --> 00:22:24.439
that's linked to this app.py file,

00:22:24.439 --> 00:22:28.439
and it will have a Docker file generated

00:22:29.439 --> 00:22:32.439
that essentially will work out of the box.

00:22:32.439 --> 00:22:37.439
This is really nice because it makes kind of that deployment struggle

00:22:37.439 --> 00:22:42.439
a little easier for data scientists to have these tools in hand.

00:22:42.439 --> 00:22:44.439
You can bring your Docker file and send it off.

00:22:44.439 --> 00:22:49.439
A lot of cloud providers have a bring-your-own-container platform.

00:22:49.439 --> 00:22:52.439
And we're also working on specialized Docker containers

00:22:52.439 --> 00:22:56.439
for different products inside cloud environments,

00:22:56.439 --> 00:22:58.439
such as AWS Lambda.

00:22:58.439 --> 00:23:02.439
So in the future, if you look at, like, write Docker Lambda,

00:23:02.439 --> 00:23:07.439
that might be something we'll be able to have for you.

00:23:07.439 --> 00:23:10.439
So your model is deployed.

00:23:10.439 --> 00:23:13.439
But a data scientist's work is not done yet.

00:23:13.439 --> 00:23:16.439
You have to do continuous monitoring to make sure that this model

00:23:16.439 --> 00:23:20.439
continues to perform the way you expect it to.

00:23:20.439 --> 00:23:22.439
And that's because data drifts.

00:23:22.439 --> 00:23:25.439
People's preferences change.

00:23:25.439 --> 00:23:32.439
If we had a model deployed that was trained on the yellow circles,

00:23:32.439 --> 00:23:34.439
our model works pretty well.

00:23:34.439 --> 00:23:38.439
But if preferences change and now we're looking at these purple triangles,

00:23:38.439 --> 00:23:41.439
our model is not doing very well anymore.

00:23:41.439 --> 00:23:46.439
And this is important to track because if your model's performances

00:23:46.439 --> 00:23:49.439
start decaying, there might not be an error.

00:23:49.439 --> 00:23:52.439
This is another one of these things where we have to think about

00:23:52.439 --> 00:23:55.439
software engineering and data scientists.

00:23:55.439 --> 00:23:59.439
When software engineers are making applications, most of the time,

00:23:59.439 --> 00:24:02.439
when things fail, they fail very loudly.

00:24:02.439 --> 00:24:04.439
You get read errors.

00:24:04.439 --> 00:24:08.439
You get calls at 3 a.m., like, why is everything broken?

00:24:08.439 --> 00:24:10.439
But models fail silently.

00:24:10.439 --> 00:24:14.439
They can still run forever and ever with no error,

00:24:14.439 --> 00:24:17.439
even if your accuracy is 0%.

00:24:17.439 --> 00:24:21.439
And we keep giving you predictions even if they're horrible.

00:24:21.439 --> 00:24:25.439
So if you're not monitoring your model in some way,

00:24:25.439 --> 00:24:30.439
you are oblivious to the decay that may be occurring.

00:24:30.439 --> 00:24:34.439
So we'll set the scene.

00:24:34.439 --> 00:24:38.439
Our YouTube-like predictor has been in production for years now.

00:24:38.439 --> 00:24:42.439
We are really happy with its performance,

00:24:42.439 --> 00:24:45.439
but we want to keep monitoring and making sure that this is working

00:24:45.439 --> 00:24:47.439
the way we expect it to.

00:24:47.439 --> 00:24:49.439
So we're going to start with a few things.

00:24:49.439 --> 00:24:53.439
We have new data, and this is a data frame that has been collected,

00:24:53.439 --> 00:24:56.439
however, maybe through data engineering pipelines.

00:24:56.439 --> 00:24:59.439
And it has a few columns that we have to give to Vetiver,

00:24:59.439 --> 00:25:02.439
the Vetiver compute metrics function.

00:25:02.439 --> 00:25:06.439
And the first column name that we have to say is the name of the date.

00:25:06.439 --> 00:25:09.439
So this is a very specific flavor of date.

00:25:09.439 --> 00:25:15.439
A lot of times, models will use time as an input to the model.

00:25:15.439 --> 00:25:20.439
However, this is actually not the input data that you are predicting on.

00:25:20.439 --> 00:25:24.439
This is the date that the prediction was made.

00:25:24.439 --> 00:25:28.439
We also need to know the true value of the like count

00:25:28.439 --> 00:25:30.439
as well as the predicted value.

00:25:30.439 --> 00:25:35.439
So we can compare these two to see if our model is still performing well.

00:25:35.439 --> 00:25:39.439
There are a few other things, like the time delta.

00:25:39.439 --> 00:25:44.439
So this is how we are aggregating this time.

00:25:44.439 --> 00:25:48.439
So this is looking at every one week, how is this data performing?

00:25:48.439 --> 00:25:50.439
And we're going to give it a metric set.

00:25:50.439 --> 00:25:53.439
Here we have mean absolute error and mean squared error

00:25:53.439 --> 00:25:55.439
from the scikit-learn metrics.

00:25:55.439 --> 00:25:57.439
These could just as well be custom metrics

00:25:57.439 --> 00:26:01.439
as long as they have a y true and y predicted value.

00:26:01.439 --> 00:26:07.439
So new data, we're going to have predicted our time delta

00:26:07.439 --> 00:26:10.439
and our metric set.

00:26:10.439 --> 00:26:12.439
And then we're going to plot these values.

00:26:12.439 --> 00:26:15.439
And this kind of has a super simple pipeline.

00:26:15.439 --> 00:26:19.439
The output of the vetiver compute metrics can go directly into plotting.

00:26:19.439 --> 00:26:22.439
But it is just a plotly graph.

00:26:22.439 --> 00:26:25.439
The beauty of open source is that it can be very, very flexible.

00:26:25.439 --> 00:26:29.439
So we can update the y-axis, we can change the colors,

00:26:29.439 --> 00:26:32.439
or do whatever else we need to make sure

00:26:32.439 --> 00:26:34.439
that this graph looks to our liking.

00:26:34.439 --> 00:26:38.439
So when we show this graph, it'll look something like this.

00:26:38.439 --> 00:26:41.439
And we can kind of hover over things,

00:26:41.439 --> 00:26:44.439
see how it's been performing in 2014, 2015.

00:26:44.439 --> 00:26:49.439
I wouldn't place any bets on how well this model is working.

00:26:49.439 --> 00:26:52.439
But here's our monitoring so that we know

00:26:52.439 --> 00:26:56.439
that we can't place any bets, that it's not working.

00:26:56.439 --> 00:26:59.439
On the R side, there's also helper functions

00:26:59.439 --> 00:27:02.439
to get you a template of a dashboard.

00:27:02.439 --> 00:27:04.439
So this has three tabs that we're going through.

00:27:04.439 --> 00:27:08.439
The first one is that same line graph that we saw earlier.

00:27:08.439 --> 00:27:12.439
The second one is a placeholder for a custom plot.

00:27:12.439 --> 00:27:15.439
So whatever you want to be looking at when you're monitoring your model,

00:27:15.439 --> 00:27:18.439
you can just continue to add these tabs.

00:27:18.439 --> 00:27:22.439
Because this dashboard is actually just R code.

00:27:22.439 --> 00:27:27.439
But as flexible as you can program your R script.

00:27:27.439 --> 00:27:30.439
The last tab is API visual documentation.

00:27:30.439 --> 00:27:34.439
It's the same things that we saw a few slides ago.

00:27:34.439 --> 00:27:38.439
And it is right there.

00:27:38.439 --> 00:27:40.439
Very quickly.

00:27:40.439 --> 00:27:42.439
So this is just to kind of ground people.

00:27:42.439 --> 00:27:45.439
You know what model you're using, you know where it's living,

00:27:45.439 --> 00:27:49.439
and you can interact with it in this dashboard.

00:27:50.439 --> 00:27:54.439
So what happens when things go wrong?

00:27:54.439 --> 00:27:56.439
We were monitoring for when things go wrong,

00:27:56.439 --> 00:27:58.439
but like, oh no, it's happened now.

00:27:58.439 --> 00:28:00.439
What do we do?

00:28:00.439 --> 00:28:03.439
The first step is almost always to retrain your model.

00:28:03.439 --> 00:28:07.439
If your data has drifted and you've chosen kind of the appropriate data

00:28:07.439 --> 00:28:09.439
or the appropriate model,

00:28:09.439 --> 00:28:10.439
the data structure kind of looks the same.

00:28:10.439 --> 00:28:13.439
Retraining, most of the time, works very well

00:28:13.439 --> 00:28:16.439
and you can continue on with your life.

00:28:16.439 --> 00:28:20.439
However, sometimes you need to try a new model type.

00:28:20.439 --> 00:28:24.439
So this is important if things have changed,

00:28:24.439 --> 00:28:28.439
retraining isn't working, here's another plan of action.

00:28:28.439 --> 00:28:32.439
However, you always have to remember to version.

00:28:32.439 --> 00:28:35.439
Because these are strongly versioned APIs,

00:28:35.439 --> 00:28:37.439
if we want to roll back or move forward

00:28:37.439 --> 00:28:40.439
in case, you know, performance goes bad again,

00:28:40.439 --> 00:28:41.439
we need to go back to a different model.

00:28:41.439 --> 00:28:44.439
This is really important for that stability

00:28:44.439 --> 00:28:46.439
and those good software engineering practices

00:28:46.439 --> 00:28:50.439
that we want to integrate into our data science workflow.

00:28:53.439 --> 00:28:56.439
So MLOps is thinking about making good models.

00:28:56.439 --> 00:29:00.439
Now, of course, we want to have statistically good models.

00:29:00.439 --> 00:29:03.439
That's hopefully a given.

00:29:03.439 --> 00:29:09.439
But we also want to have models that are giving a nod to ethics.

00:29:09.439 --> 00:29:13.439
There's no surefire way to avoid bias.

00:29:13.439 --> 00:29:17.439
But thinking about it is a good place to start.

00:29:17.439 --> 00:29:20.439
This is a space that my team has been actively investing in

00:29:20.439 --> 00:29:23.439
and trying to figure out how we can make tools

00:29:23.439 --> 00:29:26.439
that really give data scientists best practices

00:29:26.439 --> 00:29:30.439
in not only a statistical sense, but an ethical one.

00:29:30.439 --> 00:29:32.439
So we saw this earlier.

00:29:32.439 --> 00:29:35.439
So vetiver, pinwrite, we're writing this pin to our board.

00:29:35.439 --> 00:29:39.439
But what I actually had hidden is the fact that this pops up.

00:29:39.439 --> 00:29:41.439
It says model cards are a framework

00:29:41.439 --> 00:29:43.439
for transparent, responsible reporting.

00:29:43.439 --> 00:29:45.439
And it says to use this function

00:29:45.439 --> 00:29:48.439
if you want to use this quarto template.

00:29:48.439 --> 00:29:54.439
So model cards were created from a team at Google.

00:29:54.439 --> 00:29:55.439
I think they left Google.

00:29:55.439 --> 00:30:00.439
And they realized that there is a more holistic view of models

00:30:00.439 --> 00:30:03.439
that maybe isn't captured oftentimes.

00:30:03.439 --> 00:30:06.439
So if you run this vetiver model card,

00:30:06.439 --> 00:30:09.439
you get a partially automated quarto template

00:30:09.439 --> 00:30:12.439
that's similar to or same thing as what my slides are.

00:30:12.439 --> 00:30:16.439
And quarto is a technical documentation platform.

00:30:16.439 --> 00:30:18.439
It's pretty easy to install.

00:30:18.439 --> 00:30:20.439
It kind of feels like a Jupyter notebook,

00:30:20.439 --> 00:30:22.439
but it's multilingual in a different way.

00:30:22.439 --> 00:30:25.439
And it can make slides, which is fun.

00:30:25.439 --> 00:30:28.439
So we're going to make this model card.

00:30:28.439 --> 00:30:30.439
And it's partially automated

00:30:30.439 --> 00:30:33.439
in the places where we were able to automate things.

00:30:33.439 --> 00:30:35.439
But it also gives a lot of space

00:30:35.439 --> 00:30:37.439
for data scientists to jot down their thoughts.

00:30:37.439 --> 00:30:39.439
So you can see I have...

00:30:39.439 --> 00:30:42.439
It's generated that we have a scikit-learn pipeline model.

00:30:42.439 --> 00:30:43.439
It's got four features.

00:30:43.439 --> 00:30:46.439
We can see the time the version was created.

00:30:46.439 --> 00:30:51.439
And you can put in your email and stuff like that.

00:30:51.439 --> 00:30:53.439
If you scroll down further,

00:30:53.439 --> 00:30:55.439
you can see that there's stuff on training data

00:30:55.439 --> 00:30:56.439
and evaluation data.

00:30:56.439 --> 00:30:59.439
We have a printout of what the p-type looks like.

00:30:59.439 --> 00:31:01.439
This is for a different model.

00:31:01.439 --> 00:31:05.439
But you can see kind of the title, the default, the type.

00:31:05.439 --> 00:31:08.439
And we can also look at quantitative analyses.

00:31:08.439 --> 00:31:10.439
So we'll look at the model performance.

00:31:10.439 --> 00:31:13.439
We'll look at the disaggregated model performance.

00:31:13.439 --> 00:31:16.439
So how does this model perform on different groups?

00:31:16.439 --> 00:31:18.439
We can also visualize the model performance,

00:31:18.439 --> 00:31:19.439
which is out of the box.

00:31:19.439 --> 00:31:22.439
There's also a space for you to put custom plots.

00:31:22.439 --> 00:31:25.439
Once again, this is just code.

00:31:25.439 --> 00:31:27.439
So you're able to edit this

00:31:27.439 --> 00:31:31.439
and change things up as much as you need to.

00:31:31.439 --> 00:31:33.439
If you scroll all the way down to the bottom,

00:31:33.439 --> 00:31:35.439
there's a very important piece.

00:31:35.439 --> 00:31:37.439
And it says ethical considerations

00:31:37.439 --> 00:31:40.439
and caveats and recommendations.

00:31:40.439 --> 00:31:43.439
So our model for predicting likes on YouTube,

00:31:43.439 --> 00:31:47.439
we might not think that it has any ethical challenges.

00:31:47.439 --> 00:31:50.439
But I'll give two pieces of advice to that thought.

00:31:50.439 --> 00:31:53.439
One is you should probably check with the people

00:31:53.439 --> 00:31:55.439
that your model is impacting,

00:31:55.439 --> 00:31:57.439
especially marginalized groups

00:31:57.439 --> 00:31:59.439
where this might be impacting differently

00:31:59.439 --> 00:32:01.439
than the general population.

00:32:01.439 --> 00:32:04.439
And even if you have done all of the surveys,

00:32:04.439 --> 00:32:06.439
you've done your due diligence,

00:32:06.439 --> 00:32:09.439
and you find that there are really no ethical considerations,

00:32:09.439 --> 00:32:14.439
I would recommend that you don't delete this section.

00:32:14.439 --> 00:32:18.439
Even if you have imprecise or imperfect information,

00:32:18.439 --> 00:32:20.439
just writing down your thought process

00:32:20.439 --> 00:32:23.439
or what you've thought about

00:32:23.439 --> 00:32:27.439
for the ethical considerations and recommendations,

00:32:27.439 --> 00:32:30.439
it's important.

00:32:30.439 --> 00:32:34.439
So the processes of documenting,

00:32:34.439 --> 00:32:36.439
they're limited by the data scientist,

00:32:36.439 --> 00:32:39.439
so this is really only as useful as you want to make it.

00:32:39.439 --> 00:32:41.439
But I think, so my dad has a quote.

00:32:41.439 --> 00:32:43.439
He's been telling me this all my life,

00:32:43.439 --> 00:32:45.439
and I'm going to share it with you guys

00:32:45.439 --> 00:32:47.439
because I think it's important here.

00:32:47.439 --> 00:32:50.439
If you haven't written it down, you haven't thought it out.

00:32:50.439 --> 00:32:53.439
Model cards are a great way to collect your thoughts,

00:32:53.439 --> 00:32:56.439
to think about your model in a really holistic way

00:32:56.439 --> 00:32:59.439
that I think is really important.

00:33:00.439 --> 00:33:03.439
So from the ground up, what is MLOps?

00:33:03.439 --> 00:33:06.439
I hope by now you realize that it's a set of practices,

00:33:06.439 --> 00:33:09.439
and we've gone over a few practices here.

00:33:09.439 --> 00:33:14.439
So what do we have to keep in mind when looking at tools?

00:33:14.439 --> 00:33:16.439
Oh, that's fine.

00:33:16.439 --> 00:33:19.439
So we're going to fast-forward a week from the conference.

00:33:19.439 --> 00:33:22.439
We're also going to be looking at my speaker notes right here.

00:33:22.439 --> 00:33:25.439
So we're going to need a few tools, and we're all scientists,

00:33:25.439 --> 00:33:27.439
and we're going to do our good research.

00:33:27.439 --> 00:33:30.439
And our good research is going to include a Google search

00:33:30.439 --> 00:33:33.439
for what does the MLOps landscape look like.

00:33:33.439 --> 00:33:35.439
And you're going to get something like this.

00:33:35.439 --> 00:33:38.439
And you're going to realize this landscape is crazy,

00:33:38.439 --> 00:33:44.439
and there's no one-size-fits-all tool for what your team needs.

00:33:44.439 --> 00:33:48.439
I've shown you Vetiver, but there are lots of other options.

00:33:48.439 --> 00:33:50.439
So I make data science tools,

00:33:50.439 --> 00:33:55.439
but I've also thought a lot about what do other tools do

00:33:55.439 --> 00:33:58.439
and what's important to keep in mind.

00:33:58.439 --> 00:34:03.439
The first thing is that you and your team are unique.

00:34:03.439 --> 00:34:07.439
So I've talked to a lot of different data scientists and customers,

00:34:07.439 --> 00:34:11.439
and for some teams, just having a pinned model

00:34:11.439 --> 00:34:13.439
kind of up in a cloud somewhere

00:34:13.439 --> 00:34:17.439
that helps people collaborate with each other is amazing.

00:34:17.439 --> 00:34:22.439
And that's the ML practices that that team needed.

00:34:22.439 --> 00:34:25.439
For other people, it's deploying a model,

00:34:25.439 --> 00:34:29.439
and it's monitoring that model, and that works for them.

00:34:29.439 --> 00:34:34.439
And there's a great span of things between these two.

00:34:34.439 --> 00:34:37.439
So think about what your team needs.

00:34:37.439 --> 00:34:41.439
You also might want to think about looking for tools that are composable.

00:34:41.439 --> 00:34:44.439
So you want to have tools that are working in different environments.

00:34:44.439 --> 00:34:48.439
I showed you Vetiver will work in a local environment.

00:34:48.439 --> 00:34:50.439
It'll work in RStudio Connect.

00:34:50.439 --> 00:34:53.439
It'll work in a variety of public clouds.

00:34:53.439 --> 00:34:59.439
And we also want this to work well with other tools.

00:34:59.439 --> 00:35:07.439
So if we have maybe different open-source tools that are out there,

00:35:07.439 --> 00:35:10.439
we want this to be composable to put these pieces together.

00:35:10.439 --> 00:35:16.439
I think a good example of this is Pandas and Scikit-learn do this amazingly.

00:35:16.439 --> 00:35:20.439
Pandas and Scikit-learn both use this data structure called a data frame.

00:35:20.439 --> 00:35:22.439
And it kind of just makes sense.

00:35:22.439 --> 00:35:24.439
You think about it, and you're like, oh, yeah,

00:35:24.439 --> 00:35:28.439
like I just put my data frame in Scikit-learn,

00:35:28.439 --> 00:35:30.439
and my model is trained.

00:35:30.439 --> 00:35:37.439
But think for just a moment how insane the Python data science ecosystem

00:35:37.439 --> 00:35:44.439
would look like if those two packages did not agree on a common data structure.

00:35:44.439 --> 00:35:47.439
In the same way, you can use Vetiver alone

00:35:47.439 --> 00:35:50.439
to do the tasks of versioning, deploying, and monitoring,

00:35:50.439 --> 00:35:53.439
but you can add in other tools that are out there

00:35:53.439 --> 00:35:57.439
that help you build the system that you need.

00:35:57.439 --> 00:36:01.439
It's also important to have tools that are composable with themselves.

00:36:01.439 --> 00:36:06.439
We looked at a pretty straightforward MLOps use case today,

00:36:06.439 --> 00:36:10.439
but you can actually layer and add in different pieces

00:36:10.439 --> 00:36:13.439
if you want an API with multiple endpoints,

00:36:13.439 --> 00:36:16.439
if you want an API that does post-processing.

00:36:16.439 --> 00:36:19.439
You can put Vetiver together with itself,

00:36:19.439 --> 00:36:27.439
kind of like Lego blocks, to create a very complex system.

00:36:27.439 --> 00:36:29.439
Reproducibility is important.

00:36:29.439 --> 00:36:34.439
And I can point to about, well, any textbook about machine learning,

00:36:34.439 --> 00:36:39.439
and they'll tell you that it's important that your machine learning model

00:36:39.439 --> 00:36:42.439
is reproducible, and the same goes for MLOps.

00:36:42.439 --> 00:36:47.439
But I do want to highlight the reproducibility of open source.

00:36:47.439 --> 00:36:50.439
So we saw the landscape slide a few moments ago,

00:36:50.439 --> 00:36:55.439
and there's a lot of options out in the MLOps space today.

00:36:55.439 --> 00:36:58.439
From a business perspective, open source is important

00:36:58.439 --> 00:37:01.439
because open source is forever.

00:37:01.439 --> 00:37:05.439
It will outlast all of us as long as the Internet is here,

00:37:05.439 --> 00:37:07.439
also because it's free and companies love that.

00:37:07.439 --> 00:37:13.439
But this is important that the lifetime of an open source project is so long

00:37:13.439 --> 00:37:17.439
because even if the company that supports it changes,

00:37:17.439 --> 00:37:21.439
you can still use the same code.

00:37:21.439 --> 00:37:26.439
From a human perspective, open source is for everyone.

00:37:26.439 --> 00:37:28.439
Once again, it's free.

00:37:28.439 --> 00:37:32.439
And second, this is a great equalizer for people who need it.

00:37:32.439 --> 00:37:41.439
As long as you have Internet connection and the courage to open an issue

00:37:41.439 --> 00:37:47.439
or connect with people, this is an amazing space for people to build skills

00:37:47.439 --> 00:37:53.439
in high-tech areas such as machine learning operations.

00:37:53.439 --> 00:37:56.439
And finally, you should be looking at tools that are ergonomic.

00:37:56.439 --> 00:38:01.439
Your need here is that you are ready to implement some MLOps practices.

00:38:01.439 --> 00:38:06.439
Your tool is going to help you do that by some magic of engineering,

00:38:06.439 --> 00:38:10.439
but we are humans and we have finite capabilities,

00:38:10.439 --> 00:38:18.439
and we need a tool that feels natural to us to complete this task.

00:38:18.439 --> 00:38:21.439
Your tool needs to fit the person,

00:38:21.439 --> 00:38:26.439
and people need to have a tool that feels good to use.

00:38:26.439 --> 00:38:30.439
Veniver is a tool that was made for data scientists in mind.

00:38:30.439 --> 00:38:34.439
It should feel like a natural extension of the workflow you're already using

00:38:34.439 --> 00:38:36.439
in Python or R.

00:38:36.439 --> 00:38:38.439
But not all tools are built for data scientists,

00:38:38.439 --> 00:38:40.439
and I think that's a good thing.

00:38:40.439 --> 00:38:44.439
So I think it's important for people to realize that maybe you need to look

00:38:44.439 --> 00:38:49.439
for a tool that works well for who you are and the persona that you bring,

00:38:49.439 --> 00:38:52.439
whether that's a software engineer, whether that's a data scientist,

00:38:52.439 --> 00:38:54.439
or a data engineer.

00:38:54.439 --> 00:38:59.439
And of course, this goes for any tools, not just machine learning operations tools.

00:38:59.439 --> 00:39:03.439
And you also want a tool that can do the tasks that you want.

00:39:03.439 --> 00:39:07.439
It is a broad space, and it covers a lot of ground.

00:39:07.439 --> 00:39:11.439
And there's different sections that different tools are highlighting.

00:39:11.439 --> 00:39:17.439
Some MLOps tools are just focused on the pipelines to get data from place to place.

00:39:17.439 --> 00:39:23.439
Other tools are important because they want to think about experiment tracking.

00:39:23.439 --> 00:39:25.439
So when you're tuning your hyperparameters,

00:39:25.439 --> 00:39:28.439
logging every single one of those.

00:39:28.439 --> 00:39:35.439
So it's important that you have the tools that do the things that you want to do.

00:39:35.439 --> 00:39:37.439
All right.

00:39:37.439 --> 00:39:42.439
So we understand what MLOps is, and we know what to keep in mind for tooling.

00:39:42.439 --> 00:39:47.439
And as a quick recap, there are practices such as versioning,

00:39:47.439 --> 00:39:49.439
deploying, and monitoring.

00:39:49.439 --> 00:39:52.439
We're keeping models in production reliably and efficiently,

00:39:52.439 --> 00:39:59.439
hoping to lower the cognitive load of people's data science full life cycle.

00:39:59.439 --> 00:40:03.439
Vetiver can help you with this for R and Python.

00:40:03.439 --> 00:40:05.439
If you're interested in learning more,

00:40:05.439 --> 00:40:10.439
you can check out the documentation at vetiver.rstudio.com.

00:40:10.439 --> 00:40:13.439
You can click on this link in the slides.

00:40:13.439 --> 00:40:17.439
There is a recent screencast by my colleague, Julia Silke.

00:40:17.439 --> 00:40:21.439
She deploys a model with Docker in this YouTube video.

00:40:21.439 --> 00:40:27.439
There's also end-to-end demos from our solutions engineering teams in both R and Python.

00:40:27.439 --> 00:40:28.439
These links are to the GitHub repo.

00:40:28.439 --> 00:40:31.439
You can download them, you can run them yourselves,

00:40:31.439 --> 00:40:36.439
and really just kind of learn about what this space looks like.

00:40:36.439 --> 00:40:38.439
Also, you can visit these slides.

00:40:38.439 --> 00:40:41.439
Here is the link to these slides.

00:40:41.439 --> 00:40:44.439
And I hope you guys all learned something and that you can walk away

00:40:44.439 --> 00:40:47.439
feeling like you have some of the vocabulary and knowledge

00:40:47.439 --> 00:40:50.439
to start these conversations about MLOps.

00:40:50.439 --> 00:40:52.439
Thank you.

