00:41:10.439 --> 00:41:14.439
How do you see Vetiver versus MLflow?

00:41:14.439 --> 00:41:16.439
I love this question.

00:41:16.439 --> 00:41:22.439
So MLflow is another machine learning operations framework.

00:41:22.439 --> 00:41:26.439
And it is focused kind of in a little bit different ways.

00:41:26.439 --> 00:41:31.439
So MLflow has invested a lot of knowledge for experiment tracking.

00:41:31.439 --> 00:41:35.439
And they do such a great job, and it's super fun to play around with.

00:41:35.439 --> 00:41:39.439
So when you're training your model, it will log every single hyperparameter.

00:41:39.439 --> 00:41:44.439
I think the difference here is MLflow has put a lot of emphasis

00:41:44.439 --> 00:41:47.439
on this part of the data science life cycle.

00:41:47.439 --> 00:41:51.439
And Vetiver is interested in kind of helping the deployment side.

00:41:51.439 --> 00:41:59.439
So it's only a few lines of code to get from your model to an API endpoint.

00:41:59.439 --> 00:42:00.439
And I think that's the difference.

00:42:00.439 --> 00:42:03.439
Vetiver is focused maybe more on deploying,

00:42:03.439 --> 00:42:08.439
where MLflow has really put a lot of emphasis on experiment tracking.

00:42:08.439 --> 00:42:10.439
Great. Thank you.

00:42:10.439 --> 00:42:11.439
Our next question.

00:42:11.439 --> 00:42:15.439
What do you think about versioning Jupyter Notebook?

00:42:15.439 --> 00:42:20.439
How to do it right when trying to develop new model interactively

00:42:20.439 --> 00:42:22.439
but still have the history?

00:42:22.439 --> 00:42:25.439
Do you know what they're getting at there?

00:42:25.439 --> 00:42:28.439
I'm going to try.

00:42:28.439 --> 00:42:31.439
If this is not the answer you're looking for, feel free.

00:42:31.439 --> 00:42:35.439
I think on the website I have plenty of ways to reach me online,

00:42:35.439 --> 00:42:37.439
and I'm happy to talk about this.

00:42:38.439 --> 00:42:41.439
So Vetiver itself is not necessarily interested

00:42:41.439 --> 00:42:44.439
in versioning the whole Jupyter Notebook.

00:42:44.439 --> 00:42:49.439
I'm not quite sure of a reason why you'd want to version the whole thing

00:42:49.439 --> 00:42:51.439
besides maybe pieces of it.

00:42:51.439 --> 00:42:54.439
You want to version the data if you're training with data.

00:42:54.439 --> 00:42:58.439
You want to version your model.

00:42:58.439 --> 00:43:04.439
But the Jupyter Notebook is kind of just like the means to an end.

00:43:04.439 --> 00:43:06.439
So I would say to do this right,

00:43:06.439 --> 00:43:12.439
take out the pieces that need to be versioned, such as data or models,

00:43:12.439 --> 00:43:17.439
and put them somewhere else that's not inside a Jupyter Notebook.

00:43:17.439 --> 00:43:19.439
That's my answer for you.

00:43:19.439 --> 00:43:22.439
Feel free to reach out if that's not the question you're asking, though.

