00:47:06.439 --> 00:47:08.439
How does Vetiver determine your Python dependencies

00:47:08.439 --> 00:47:11.439
for the Dockerfile?

00:47:11.439 --> 00:47:15.439
You can do this a few different ways.

00:47:15.439 --> 00:47:16.439
I love that answer.

00:47:16.439 --> 00:47:18.439
For pretty much anything in open source,

00:47:18.439 --> 00:47:21.439
it's like you have multiple options.

00:47:21.439 --> 00:47:22.439
Inside of Vetiver,

00:47:22.439 --> 00:47:26.439
there is another function called load packages,

00:47:26.439 --> 00:47:28.439
and it will peek into your environment,

00:47:28.439 --> 00:47:33.439
and it will create a requirements.txt for you.

00:47:33.439 --> 00:47:35.439
I realize that a lot of times data scientists

00:47:35.439 --> 00:47:37.439
are already doing this by themselves,

00:47:37.439 --> 00:47:39.439
so I didn't want it to be a strong dependency

00:47:39.439 --> 00:47:41.439
of creating a Dockerfile.

00:47:41.439 --> 00:47:44.439
So you can either use that function,

00:47:44.439 --> 00:47:47.439
so you would do vetiver.writeapp, vetiver.loadpackages,

00:47:47.439 --> 00:47:51.439
and then write your Dockerfile,

00:47:51.439 --> 00:47:55.439
or you could just build your requirements yourself.

00:47:55.439 --> 00:47:56.439
Okay.

00:47:56.439 --> 00:48:03.439
And what could be the main pitfalls for versioning?

